Yeah.

34
00:02:17,140 --> 00:02:18,410
Anyway, specifically,

35
00:02:18,470 --> 00:02:22,170
we are deep inside
the Arctic Circle in Finland.

36
00:02:22,310 --> 00:02:24,340
(CHEERING)

37
00:02:24,410 --> 00:02:27,580
There you go.
And Finland, of course...

38
00:02:27,650 --> 00:02:33,460
Finland, of course, is home
to every single racing driver
currently...

39
00:02:33,520 --> 00:02:35,050
-What?
-What, all of them?

40
00:02:35,120 --> 00:02:36,350
(LAUGHTER)

41
00:02:36,420 --> 00:02:39,190
Well, apart from
Nico Rosberg, who is Finnish,

42
00:02:39,330 --> 00:02:41,630
but, for some reason,
claims he's German.

43
00:02:41,700 --> 00:02:43,700
(JEERING)

44
00:02:43,760 --> 00:02:46,330
Why does he do that?
I have no idea.

45
00:02:46,400 --> 00:02:47,560
Who else is there, then?

46
00:02:47,640 --> 00:02:48,840
Well, there's Mika Salo,

47
00:02:48,900 --> 00:02:50,630
Mika Häkkinen,
Kimi Räikkönen.

48
00:02:50,700 --> 00:02:53,370
Hang on, they're just
anagrams of the same name,
aren't they?

49
00:02:53,440 --> 00:02:55,370
-(LAUGHTER)
-Then you've got rallying.

50
00:02:55,440 --> 00:02:57,710
There's Tommi Mäkinen,
Timo Mäkinen,

51
00:02:57,780 --> 00:03:00,190
Juha Kankkunen, Ari Vatanen.

52
00:03:00,350 --> 00:03:01,750
More anagrams.

53
00:03:01,820 --> 00:03:02,960
(LAUGHTER)

54
00:03:03,020 --> 00:03:04,720
Kinky Wankinen.

55
00:03:04,790 --> 00:03:06,360
(LAUGHTER)

56
00:03:07,390 --> 00:03:09,060
Manky Pantiden.

57
00:03:09,120 --> 00:03:10,690
(LAUGHS) Really?

58
00:03:10,760 --> 00:03:12,870
I'm getting
slightly carried away now.

59
00:03:12,930 --> 00:03:15,130
Seriously, I went on
Wikipedia last night

60
00:03:15,200 --> 00:03:18,370
to look for famous Finns
who aren't racing drivers.

61
00:03:18,400 --> 00:03:19,710
Put up the list I found.

62
00:03:19,770 --> 00:03:22,440
And I noticed something -
they're all men.

63
00:03:22,500 --> 00:03:24,470
-(LAUGHTER)
-All of them.

64
00:03:24,540 --> 00:03:26,780
Are there any famous
Finnish women?

65
00:03:28,140 --> 00:03:29,270
-(MUTTERING)
-Finnish people?

66
00:03:29,380 --> 00:03:30,520
(LAUGHTER)

67
00:03:30,580 --> 00:03:33,420
Nobody thinks so.
They're all... (GRUNTS)

68
00:03:33,480 --> 00:03:34,740
I know why, OK?

69
00:03:34,820 --> 00:03:38,460
It's because all Finnish
women, at the age of 19,

70
00:03:38,520 --> 00:03:40,130
move to England
to be au pairs.

71
00:03:40,190 --> 00:03:41,860
(LAUGHTER)

72
00:03:41,920 --> 00:03:44,750
I actually had three Finnish
au pairs over the years
for my children.

73
00:03:44,830 --> 00:03:46,530
-Did you?
-Yeah. It was always funny.

74
00:03:46,590 --> 00:03:49,190
You'd go to Heathrow airport
to pick up your new au pair,

75
00:03:49,260 --> 00:03:53,300
and there'd always be a row
of 30-something fathers
waiting at the gate

76
00:03:53,400 --> 00:03:56,430
for their Scandinavian
au pair to come out.

77
00:03:56,500 --> 00:03:57,800
(LAUGHTER)

78
00:03:57,870 --> 00:03:59,900
And there was one year
I've never forgotten.

79
00:03:59,970 --> 00:04:03,610
This huge moose
lumbered out of the door,

80
00:04:03,680 --> 00:04:08,150
and the man next to me looked
at his piece of paper and
went, "Oh, for God's sake!"

81
00:04:08,220 --> 00:04:09,560
(LAUGHTER)

82
00:04:11,250 --> 00:04:12,450
That's not good.

83
00:04:16,820 --> 00:04:19,050
-Shall we get on with
the show?
-Yes, good idea.

84
00:04:19,130 --> 00:04:23,570
Because tonight
in our television
programme about cars...

85
00:04:23,630 --> 00:04:25,530
I eat some cheddar.

86
00:04:27,600 --> 00:04:30,030
Richard says
he doesn't want any.

87
00:04:30,100 --> 00:04:32,130
I don't want cheese.

88
00:04:32,210 --> 00:04:37,720
And James compares
a Ford GT40 to a Ferrari P3.

89
00:04:37,780 --> 00:04:40,290
Avanti!

90
00:04:40,350 --> 00:04:43,160
But first, if you are
watching this in America,

91
00:04:43,220 --> 00:04:44,920
you may be amazed to hear

92
00:04:44,990 --> 00:04:50,130
that the Ford Mustang
has never been sold,
officially, in the UK.

93
00:04:50,190 --> 00:04:52,860
Well, until now,
because Ford has now decided

94
00:04:52,930 --> 00:04:55,970
that the latest Mustang
will be sold in the UK

95
00:04:56,030 --> 00:04:59,140
with a V8 engine
and right-hand drive.

96
00:04:59,200 --> 00:05:03,580
Mm, and this has made
our other resident American
very happy.

97
00:05:03,640 --> 00:05:05,680
He was so excited, in fact,

98
00:05:05,740 --> 00:05:08,380
that when the first
right-hand-drive Mustang

99
00:05:08,480 --> 00:05:10,380
arrived at the docks
in the UK,

100
00:05:10,480 --> 00:05:12,790
he was actually there
to meet it.

101
00:05:12,850 --> 00:05:14,790
(LAUGHTER)

102
00:05:34,570 --> 00:05:36,510
It'll be here any minute.

103
00:05:47,920 --> 00:05:50,420
That is it. Are we ready?

104
00:05:50,520 --> 00:05:53,930
This is the moment.
It's touched down!

105
00:05:53,990 --> 00:05:54,930
Go, go, go!

106
00:05:54,990 --> 00:05:57,060
♫ New World Symphony (Dvorak)

107
00:06:02,560 --> 00:06:05,260
Look, it's a bit gloomy,
isn't it?

108
00:06:05,330 --> 00:06:08,860
It's not very welcoming.
Have you got anything
more upbeat?

109
00:06:08,940 --> 00:06:12,710
♫ When The Saints
Go Marching In

110
00:06:12,770 --> 00:06:14,540
Forget it!
Forget it! Forget it!

111
00:06:14,610 --> 00:06:16,680
-(BAND STOPS PLAYING)
-Forget it.

112
00:06:19,550 --> 00:06:21,090
(GASPS)

113
00:06:21,150 --> 00:06:23,690
I'm so excited,
my tinkle is fizzing.

114
00:06:27,560 --> 00:06:29,160
(ENGINE REVS)

115
00:06:29,220 --> 00:06:30,920
(LAUGHS)

116
00:06:30,990 --> 00:06:31,850
Oh, yeah!

117
00:06:31,930 --> 00:06:34,030
♫ National Anthem of USSR

118
00:06:37,900 --> 00:06:39,940
Oh. Sorry about that.

119
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:42,030
We really are useless
over here.

120
00:06:42,100 --> 00:06:45,070
It's one of the reasons we
needed your help in the war.

121
00:06:48,410 --> 00:06:49,980
I decided that, first of all,

122
00:06:50,040 --> 00:06:52,270
I'd show
the new Mustang around,

123
00:06:52,350 --> 00:06:54,620
so I headed for London...

124
00:06:54,680 --> 00:06:56,210
which is the capital city.

125
00:07:16,070 --> 00:07:18,780
Ah, now,
this is Tower Bridge.

126
00:07:18,840 --> 00:07:21,850
Interesting.
It's very, very old.

127
00:07:21,910 --> 00:07:24,180
But it folds
completely in half

128
00:07:24,240 --> 00:07:27,140
so that, in the old days,
the horses could go through.

129
00:07:30,780 --> 00:07:33,350
Now, that's
the Houses of Parliament,

130
00:07:33,420 --> 00:07:36,850
which are a series of houses
in which we keep
all our idiots.

131
00:07:36,920 --> 00:07:40,520
That clock thing,
that's Big Ben.

132
00:07:40,630 --> 00:07:44,740
I know it's not what you call
big, but... but we couldn't
just call it Ben.

133
00:07:46,730 --> 00:07:49,400
And that is the Cenotaph,

134
00:07:49,470 --> 00:07:53,210
where we remember those
who died fighting for us.

135
00:07:54,540 --> 00:07:56,640
Slowing down a bit here.

136
00:07:56,710 --> 00:07:58,040
Show some respect.

137
00:08:00,980 --> 00:08:03,850
No idea what that is.
It wasn't here this morning.

138
00:08:06,120 --> 00:08:08,460
A cyclist, you want to be
careful of those.

139
00:08:08,520 --> 00:08:10,790
Small
but very angry creatures.

140
00:08:13,290 --> 00:08:15,360
That's the army.

141
00:08:15,430 --> 00:08:17,700
They're the ones
who shot at your White House.

142
00:08:17,770 --> 00:08:19,000
Sorry about that.

143
00:08:20,170 --> 00:08:22,740
Having seen
all of the sights,

144
00:08:22,800 --> 00:08:24,830
we headed out of town

145
00:08:24,910 --> 00:08:26,680
so I could do this.

146
00:08:26,740 --> 00:08:28,670
(ENGINE THRUMS)

147
00:08:31,180 --> 00:08:32,690
There it is.

148
00:08:32,680 --> 00:08:36,910
That is the soundtrack
that Britain has been missing
for 51 years -

149
00:08:36,980 --> 00:08:39,310
real American V8 muscle.

150
00:08:43,390 --> 00:08:47,060
We just don't make cars like
this on our side of the pond.

151
00:08:47,130 --> 00:08:50,900
All that
lazy-but-determined torque.

152
00:08:50,960 --> 00:08:54,900
Squeeze the throttle
in any gear at any speed...

153
00:08:54,970 --> 00:08:57,440
...and there's
an inevitability
to the way it moves off.

154
00:08:57,500 --> 00:09:00,700
It's like arm wrestling
a solar system -
you're gonna lose.

155
00:09:11,350 --> 00:09:12,920
It is weird...

156
00:09:12,990 --> 00:09:16,030
driving a Mustang
from this side.

157
00:09:16,090 --> 00:09:17,800
It's like suddenly
changing your mind

158
00:09:17,860 --> 00:09:20,900
after 50 years of marriage
and sleeping on the other
side of the bed.

159
00:09:22,860 --> 00:09:25,230
It's also weird
driving a car with a big V8,

160
00:09:25,300 --> 00:09:27,370
reversing camera,
air-conditioned seats,

161
00:09:27,430 --> 00:09:32,200
rain-sensing wipers
that you can buy for £37,000.

162
00:09:32,270 --> 00:09:35,740
That's half of what you'd pay
for a BMW M4. Half.

163
00:09:39,010 --> 00:09:41,180
Once we were in
the countryside proper,

164
00:09:41,250 --> 00:09:43,760
I continued
my sightseeing tour.

165
00:09:45,190 --> 00:09:47,960
Look, I've drawn your badge
on a hill.

166
00:09:55,060 --> 00:09:56,260
Jeremy did that one.

167
00:10:00,100 --> 00:10:01,830
Sorry.

168
00:10:04,240 --> 00:10:07,180
Eventually,
we arrived at Stonehenge.

169
00:10:09,680 --> 00:10:12,450
That,
you'll be amazed to learn,

170
00:10:12,510 --> 00:10:14,480
is an ancient calendar.

171
00:10:16,320 --> 00:10:18,520
Or a clock. Or a church.

172
00:10:18,590 --> 00:10:23,260
My tour of Britain
was then interrupted
by an unwelcome arrival.

173
00:10:23,320 --> 00:10:25,450
(GROANS)

174
00:10:25,530 --> 00:10:26,770
What are you doing here?

175
00:10:26,830 --> 00:10:29,670
Well,
I have come to remind you -

176
00:10:29,730 --> 00:10:31,500
cos you've obviously
forgotten,

177
00:10:31,560 --> 00:10:32,960
cos you're too giddy -

178
00:10:33,030 --> 00:10:36,100
that we have no need
for the Mustang in Britain.

179
00:10:36,170 --> 00:10:38,280
Because if you want to spend,

180
00:10:38,340 --> 00:10:41,450
what, £30,000-£35,000
on a fast Ford,

181
00:10:41,510 --> 00:10:44,980
you'd buy a Focus RS, cos
that was designed for here.

182
00:10:45,050 --> 00:10:47,620
No, you'd settle for that
in the UK

183
00:10:47,680 --> 00:10:50,410
because you couldn't
buy this, but now you can.

184
00:10:50,480 --> 00:10:51,810
That is the point.

185
00:10:51,890 --> 00:10:53,830
Would you wear chaps?

186
00:10:53,890 --> 00:10:56,030
No, because we have trousers.

187
00:10:56,090 --> 00:10:58,060
What about cowboy...
Oh, you are. Cowboy boots.

188
00:10:58,130 --> 00:10:59,800
Well, it's appropriate.
I'm welcoming...

189
00:10:59,860 --> 00:11:03,460
Listen, I don't want
everything from America,
I just want the Mustang.

190
00:11:03,530 --> 00:11:04,690
-Stupid.
-No, America--

191
00:11:04,830 --> 00:11:06,360
It wasn't designed for here.

192
00:11:06,430 --> 00:11:08,830
-Would you wear a Stetson?
-Well, no.

193
00:11:08,840 --> 00:11:10,840
"It's cold out,
I'll wear a Stetson."

194
00:11:10,840 --> 00:11:12,740
No! You wear a bobble hat.

195
00:11:12,840 --> 00:11:14,470
That's a bobble hat.

196
00:11:14,540 --> 00:11:16,370
Oh! No, hang on.

197
00:11:17,910 --> 00:11:19,510
-I've just realised.
-What?

198
00:11:19,580 --> 00:11:22,120
Erm... I-I don't want
to talk to you any more.

199
00:11:35,360 --> 00:11:37,230
(CHEERING)

200
00:11:40,300 --> 00:11:41,860
Anyway...

201
00:11:41,940 --> 00:11:45,510
Anyway, we shall
pick that up later on.

202
00:11:45,570 --> 00:11:48,070
But right now
it's time to drop it a cog

203
00:11:48,140 --> 00:11:51,870
and hook a left
into Conversation Street.

204
00:11:51,880 --> 00:11:53,890
(MELLOW JAZZ)

205
00:11:56,780 --> 00:11:58,050
(LAUGHTER)

206
00:12:00,620 --> 00:12:03,890
-Serious. It's serious.
-It is serious stuff, this.

207
00:12:05,230 --> 00:12:07,470
Now, look, in Britain
we are always being told

208
00:12:07,530 --> 00:12:09,940
that the Scandinavians
are brilliant at driving,

209
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:13,770
and that's because they would
be, because they have
to deal with all that snow.

210
00:12:13,900 --> 00:12:17,900
Mm, they're brilliant
because what they do
most of all is crash.

211
00:12:17,970 --> 00:12:19,770
Well, you're absolutely
right, as it turns out,

212
00:12:19,910 --> 00:12:22,650
cos I've got some interesting
statistics here. Erm...

213
00:12:22,710 --> 00:12:27,220
In Britain, 1.2% of accidents
result in fatalities.

214
00:12:27,280 --> 00:12:29,910
Here, I'm afraid, it's 5.1%.

215
00:12:29,980 --> 00:12:31,910
Yeah, and it's not just
the Finns, either,

216
00:12:31,920 --> 00:12:33,930
if I may be so bold.

217
00:12:33,920 --> 00:12:36,380
Our Senior
International Producer -

218
00:12:36,460 --> 00:12:37,930
that's his job title -

219
00:12:37,960 --> 00:12:39,700
came over to Finland
the other day,

220
00:12:39,760 --> 00:12:41,830
rented himself a BMW
at the airport -

221
00:12:41,930 --> 00:12:44,170
not a Ford or an Opel,
you'll note, a BMW -

222
00:12:44,230 --> 00:12:46,460
and on his way to
the location here,

223
00:12:46,530 --> 00:12:47,800
this happened.

224
00:12:47,940 --> 00:12:50,010
-(LAUGHTER)
RICHARD: He did! He did!

225
00:12:50,070 --> 00:12:52,370
When I say he's our Senior
International Producer,

226
00:12:52,440 --> 00:12:54,950
he's now our Junior
International Producer.

227
00:12:54,980 --> 00:12:57,580
-Our Junior Local Producer.
-Yeah.

228
00:12:57,640 --> 00:13:00,340
Very local. Specifically,
the stationery cupboard.

229
00:13:00,410 --> 00:13:02,980
-He can produce that.
-That's all
he's in charge of.

230
00:13:03,050 --> 00:13:04,950
How did he do that?!

231
00:13:04,950 --> 00:13:08,350
The thing is, what I don't
understand is how the Finns
manage to go fast enough

232
00:13:08,420 --> 00:13:10,420
to have a crash
of any sort at all,

233
00:13:10,490 --> 00:13:13,690
because the speeding fines
here are insane.

234
00:13:13,760 --> 00:13:15,760
They're means tested,

235
00:13:15,830 --> 00:13:17,640
which means
a guy here recently

236
00:13:17,700 --> 00:13:20,370
was caught doing 49mph
through a 30 zone

237
00:13:20,430 --> 00:13:25,200
and he was fined
112,000 euros.

238
00:13:25,270 --> 00:13:27,140
-That's a speeding fine!
-(AUDIENCE GASPS)

239
00:13:27,210 --> 00:13:29,110
Are they really that high
in Finland?

240
00:13:29,180 --> 00:13:31,080
-(AUDIENCE CONCUR)
-They are?

241
00:13:31,140 --> 00:13:32,440
A hundred and twelve...

242
00:13:32,510 --> 00:13:33,840
112,000.

243
00:13:33,980 --> 00:13:36,580
-Imagine getting that
in the post!
-Well, it's interesting.

244
00:13:36,650 --> 00:13:39,520
Actually, there was
a Finnish minister
recently said

245
00:13:39,590 --> 00:13:42,290
that the government
needs those speeding fines

246
00:13:42,360 --> 00:13:44,630
to balance the books,
they said.

247
00:13:44,690 --> 00:13:48,090
They actually said, "Speeding
is good for the country."

248
00:13:48,160 --> 00:13:50,460
-(LAUGHTER)
-That is actually what...

249
00:13:50,530 --> 00:13:52,260
JEREMY:
Because it is. Every country.

